T2 19 Anonymous5 : Maybe tomorrow we can hear about Charles Dickens.
T2 20 AtomicSnarl : For those wondering how wild colors and stripes on ships would hide them from U-Boats -- it didn't.
T2 21 AtomicSnarl : It made it hard for the U-Boat captains to properly evaluate their targets.
T2 22 AtomicSnarl : The colors and pattern would disrupt the length, angle, and speed clues seen though binoculars at a distance, and through the periscope when preparing to fire torpedoes.
T2 23 AtomicSnarl : Radar didn't exist during WWI, so U-Boats cruised on the surface with lookouts who could eyeball ships or ship smoke at 10 miles, maybe 20 on a good day.
T2 24 AtomicSnarl : Given their 15-18 knot surface speed k12.nc.us and 6-8 knot submerged speed, the U-Boat now had only 30 minutes or so to get into proper position ahead of the approaching ship -- about 4000-6000 yards 2-3 nautical miles ahead and to one side of the approaching target.
T2 25 AtomicSnarl : WWI German torpedoes wikipedia.org could travel 6600 yards at 36 knots, for a max run time of just over 5 minutes.
T2 26 AtomicSnarl : A target ship moving at 12 knots would move 400 yards in a minute.
T2 27 AtomicSnarl : A 600 foot ship travels it's length in only 30 seconds.
T2 28 AtomicSnarl : It's this tiny window that the Razzle-Dazzle would screw up.
T2 29 AtomicSnarl : If the U-Boat captain guessed wrong on the ships movement due to painted false bow waves and extra bow/stern lines, the firing solution would be bad.
T2 30 AtomicSnarl : Remember that the ship view from the U-Boat was usually against cloudy skies of some sort in the North Atlantic.
T3 31 AtomicSnarl : Add in the blue haze with distance, and the yellows, purples, and pinks start to blur into the background blue-gray sky.
T3 32 AtomicSnarl : Now think of that sight through a wet periscope a few feet above the water, and you get the idea.
T3 33 AtomicSnarl : WWII had a brilliant camoufalge example in the bizarre sounding Pink Spitfires airplane-pictures.net used for reconnaissance ipmsstockholm.org.
T3 34 AtomicSnarl : The pink shade was selected to blend against the just-past-sunset twilight sky and clouds when those aircraft flew, and it was very effective.
