T6 74 siride : No, "thy" is quite correct here, although "sayeth" isn't.
T6 75 siride : The singular imperative quite boringly had no ending in Early Modern English or late Middle Engish -- whichever the OP was going for.
T6 76 siride : "Thine" was the original form, and over time came only to be used before words starting with a vowel or when standing alone as "mine" still is and "thy", a shortened form, was used before consonants and eventually took over as the sole adjectival form as "my" still is.
T6 77 Anonymous14 : I read about this once.
T6 78 Anonymous14 : Basically the shape of a snowflake is determined by the exact conditions over the course of the formation of the snowflake.
T6 79 Anonymous14 : This is why finding two identical snowflakes is so unlikely.
T6 80 Anonymous14 : That being said, apparently the vast majority of snow flakes aren't symmetrical.
T6 81 Anonymous14 : It's just that they aren't pretty so no one posts pictures of them.
T6 82 Anonymous14 : According to this site  run by a Caltech physics prof, its got amazing info and pictures of snowflakes, "The most common snow crystals by far are the irregular crystals.
T6 83 Anonymous14 : These are small, usually clumped together, and show little of the symmetry seen in stellar or columnar crystals.
T6 84 Anonymous14 : "In any case, the reason for the "perfect" symmetry that you can find it, "As the crystal becomes larger, however,  branches begin to sprout from the six corners of the hexagon this is the third stage in the diagram at right.
T6 85 Anonymous14 : Since the atmospheric conditions e. g. temperature and humidity are nearly constant across the small crystal, the six budding arms all grow out at roughly the same rate.
